Note. Schintlmeister (2008: 37) stated that “there is a larger distribution gap in S[outh] China and Indochina” between the Z. pannosa pannosa and Z. pannosa necopinatus . However, the specimen of “ Zaranga tukuringra Streltzov & Yakovlev, 2007 ” from Yunnan on the photo from the site “Digital Moths of Japan ” (
Yanagida et al . 2017
), likely belongs to Z. pannosa . This correlates with the supposed genetic data of this species (see above). So, Z. pannosa can inhabit at least SW China also. The figure of Z. pannosa in Hampson (1893: 147) shows a female, not a male, as indicated under the figure.
